block.comment: When the space bar is pressed, the game begins. All instructions are also detailed on the screen when it is appropriate to be used. Start game is broadcasted, which causes all the game logic sprties to start running.
Pressing r on the keyboard will reset the entire leaderboard so that they can start fresh.

Once the gameplay ends, when the bird dies, the gamer can choose to press C if they want to play another game, bringing them back to the main page but keeping their last score accounted for. This resets most of the game mechanics including pipe and coin generation.

After "Game Over" is broadcasted and received, this script will change its gameplay background to the "Game Over" background/costume as well as stop all scripts but this. It will then broadcast "Points" to run the scoreboard functions as well as making the bird speak.

custom-block.comment: Max of list is an importnat block to test because it runs a major piece of the logic that determines whether your score is a high score or not. This test was to ensure that it worked for a max value in the middle of a list.

We are testing this block because the greater than or equal to block is very importnat when we are sorting through scores to determine if the current score is a high score or not. This test helps determine if it works when the first input is less than the second.

We are testing this block because the greater than or equal to block is very importnat when we are sorting through scores to determine if the current score is a high score or not. This test helps determine if it works when the first input is equal to the second.

Max of list is an importnat block to test because it runs a major piece of the logic that determines whether your score is a high score or not. This test was to ensure that it worked for a list with multiple duplicate values

Max of list is an importnat block to test because it runs a major piece of the logic that determines whether your score is a high score or not. This test was to ensure that it worked for a max value at the end of a list.

Max of list is an importnat block to test because it runs a major piece of the logic that determines whether your score is a high score or not. This test was to ensure that it worked for a max value at the beginning of a list.

We are testing this block because the greater than or equal to block is very importnat when we are sorting through scores to determine if the current score is a high score or not. This test helps determine if it works when the first input is greater than the second.

block.comment: Once "Start Game" is broadcasted and received, this script will forever check if the PointSystem sprite is touching the DualPipes sprite. If it is, the score will change by 1 and the pipes pass through will also change by 1. This is our way of keeping track of how many times the bird/successfully passes through the pipes without touching it.

Once "Points" is broadcasted and received, it should add the numbers accordingly to the "Pipes," "Coins," and "Scores" list on "Scoreboard." "Scoreboard" can be found on the top left hand corner of the screen.
When the "Bonus" sprite receives "start game," it will randomly pick a random time from 5 to 10 secs to create a clone of the "Bonus" costume.
Once the clone is created from the above block, it is set to generate and then move horizontally from right to left where the bird/character's goal is to then touch it.
If the bird/character touches the coin, the score would change by 5 and the coin count would change by 1 on the scoreboard. The coin noise is played and the coin disappears from the screen

When the space bar is pressed, the game begins. This sprite receives the start game broadcast and brings the pipes to the front layer so the player can see them. It also starts the infinte genertaion of pipes until it is told to stop
After the clone of dual pipes is made from the script above, this script is called to make the clone move horizontally, from right to left, and delete once its off the screen to reduce lag.
This block is used to project more pipes onto the screen, given that the character/bird has not yet died. It will choose to randomly disburse another pipe anywhere from 1.2 to 1.7 seconds

If the dual pipe sprite touches the character/bird, "Game Over" will be broadcasted, which in turn, changes the current character to a ghost, states the final and top score, and the background changes to the game over costume/background.

We set number to pick random from 1 to 4, which in turn, would set the Bird sprite at the beginning of the game to any of its four costumes, christmas flappy bird, Mordecai, Superman, or a normal flappy bird
To account for gravity as a constant, the second the game starts, the bird/character will move downward by 2.8 units indefinitely.
Everytime the up arrow is pressed on the keyboard, the bird/character will move up in the y-directed by 22.4 units to counteract the force of "gravity" while the bird is jumping
When "Game Over" is broadcasted, the current costume of "Bird" will change to the ghost costume.
Once the game starts, this block will forever check to see if the bird goes above the screen shown or drops to the floor. If it does, the "Game Over" script will be broadcasted.

When points is received, an empty list called "ScoreboardPoints" is created. The numerical value of points will be added to this list. After each gameplay, it will keep all scores from this list which will then be used to determine the high score so that the last score and high score will be stated by the ghost character.

list.l: and it is the new high score!

block.comment: In addition to counteracting gravity, we used the glide block set to (-100, y+25) over a .05 interval to make the bird jump and seem as realistic as possible
